<p>I approach the matter as one who until a decade and a half ago was firmly of the Right.</p>

<p>Gradually, my thinking has changed drastically. I had strong aversion to Labour when Kinnock (a buffoon and less couth version of Boris Johnson) and Blair (I deemed him innately wicked as soon as he came to my attention) were party leaders. The Blair/Brown era was distinguished by having some of the most blatantly corrupt (moving in and out of office by revolving door) or meretricious government ministers of the post-WW2 period. Sadly, yet not unexpectedly, neither of the two governments post-Brown are exemplars of good-sense, vision, rectitude and concern for the well-being of ordinary people.</p>

<p>It was the run up to the 2008 financial collapse and the incompetent manner by which it was handled in the USA and UK that confirmed suspicions that market-capitalism was moribund and that this state had been hastened by 'deregulation' in the '80s. Thereupon, I took keen interest in non-conventional economic theory.</p>

<p>A salient feature, sadly ill-considered by politicians, of this 21st century is that it differs <i>qualitatively</i> from everything previously. The opportunities offered and challenges posed cannot be met by political, economic, and social values rooted in the 19th century and beyond.</p>

<p>Thus, to me, the concept of a political spectrum from Left to Right has become anachronistic. Indeed, solutions to pressing problems, e.g. restoring market-capitalism as a mechanism serving humanity rather than the other way around, must come from imaginative people across the alleged spectrum. No longer must always partly artificial and now wholly redundant labels (Left, Right etc) constrain imagination and prevent constructive dialogue over where we as a nation seek to go and how we should contribute to helping the world as whole grasp current opportunities.</p>

<p>In that context I welcome Mr Corbyn. I hope he can deliver on his promises with respect to the Labour Party: essentially, genuine membership participation. I hope he will foster radical discussion of economics, foreign policy, societal values, and so forth; let there be no 'sacred cows' - either of Left or Right - untouched in debate. Neither the Lib/Dem leaders nor Conservatives leaders are up to the job of grasping the true import of this 21st century. That is not to say, members and MPs of other political parties lack the ability, merely the will at present. Maybe political realignments shall occur.</p>

<p>Mr Corbyn must be on to something. Else why all the vitriolic attacks upon him through media supporting the unsustainable <i>status quo</i>?</p>

