<p>Communism is an economic and historical theory which considers social evolution superstructural to economic development and the ownership and mode of production. Progressivism is a moralist ideology based on the "reform" of the lower orders from above. Post-marxism is a theory developed after the war which applies the Marxist analysis of class struggle to social groups, in which identified "victim" classes are elevated above the identified "hegemonic" class.</p>

<p>Post-marxist progressivism asserts that all social problems are a moral issue of discrimination by hegemonic classes (white, male, straight, cis etc) against victim classes (BME, female, gay, trans etc) and thus the moral leaders of society must reform and diminish the hegemonic classes by force. Perceived wealth, status, safety etc are "privileges" of the hegemonic classes which must be removed.</p>

<p>Marx wouldn't recognise any of this. Hence, post-marxism.</p>

<p>Ian B<br/>Is what you describe as "Post-marxist progressivism the same as Cultural Marxism?</p>

<p>Sort of. PMP incorporates CM as a justifying ideology, but rather than a communist conspiracy, the root cause (in my hypothesis) is the quest for moral authority by Western elites, who grabbed onto CM as a convenient moral system after the collapse of Christianity as the basic moral system.</p>

<p>Progressivism has existed since the Victorian Era. It was particularly acute in the USA. This is the second wave of it. The first was powered by Christian values, this Second wave appeals to post-marxist (or cultural marxist, if you prefer) theory. In both cases it is a kind of "State AS Church" in which moral leadership is the defined role of government.</p>

