<p>In brief, Mr. Heffer says that Labour is now an "utterly irrelevant cult" run by malevolent nutters "under the heel of pressure groups whose views are extreme, [and] unrepresentative." I think he is only half right.</p>

<p>The problem nowadays is that the political class still imagines that people see their political views in terms of Party, with loyalty to a Party fundamentally based on the old divides between rich and poor, upper class and lower class, city and county. They have failed to understand that the introduction of the identity group power structure has swept that concept into the dustbin of history. People support the goals of their identity group leadership now, not any particular political party.</p>

<p>This is the explanation for the rise of Corbyn, and why Mr. Heffer is only half right. Corbyn is, to some degree, under the heel of extreme pressure groups, but those groups are very representative of the populace as a whole, not unrepresentative.</p>

<p>Half the population of Britain is female. Only a small minority do not see themselves as feminists, while the majority look to female identity group leadership as their real political representatives, not political parties. A significant portion of the population is made up of racial minorities, and similarly this population looks to their various identity group (pressure group) leadership for their political line. Homosexuals? Environmentalists? I could go on, but I think my point is clear.</p>

<p>And Corbyn is the representative of all these groups in Parliament. Without him, they are divided, with him they are united. He may indeed be subject to 'pressure' from these groups, but he knows he can suppress and weaken any irksome identity group leader by a simple direct appeal to that leader's constituency.</p>

<p>Thus, while Labour under Corbyn and his cronies is indeed malevolent and cultish, so is a large and growing proportion of the population. That is the true problem the political class must grapple with. They have spent fifty years creating this monster, but refuse to see that it is now alive.</p>

<p>I disagree with your views on a cult having risen, but the rest is a good analysis.</p>

<p>"Most newspapers would rather report, for the enlightenment of their readers, a church jumble sale than devote precious news pages to the antics of this utterly irrelevant cult"</p>

